## Selecting attributes
The caret package also provides functions to automatically compute the relevance and importance of attributes in your data. We can also use methods to select the most important features.
### Detect redundant attributes
In this example we use the "Pima Indians Diabetes" (mlbench library), a dataset  with a number of biological attributes from medical reports.
```{r}
set.seed(1)
# load the data
data(PimaIndiansDiabetes)
# calculate correlation matrix
correlationMatrix <- cor(PimaIndiansDiabetes[,1:8])
# summarize the correlation matrix
print(correlationMatrix)
View(PimaIndiansDiabetes)
# find attributes that are highly corrected (ideally >0.75) # identifica atributos correlacionados con otros a partir de un cierto nivel, pero es dificil mayor de 0.75/0.8, que es lo ideal, por eso aquí lo hemos bajado a 0.5
highlyCorrelated <- findCorrelation(correlationMatrix, cutoff=0.5)
# print indexes of highly correlated attributes
print(highlyCorrelated)
# return the name of the column (instead the index)
highlyCorrelated <- findCorrelation(correlationMatrix, cutoff=0.5,names=T)
print(highlyCorrelated)
# find attributes that are highly corrected (ideally >0.75) # identifica atributos correlacionados con otros a partir de un cierto nivel, pero es dificil mayor de 0.75/0.8, que es lo ideal, por eso aquí lo hemos bajado a 0.5
highlyCorrelated <- findCorrelation(correlationMatrix, cutoff=0.5)
# print indexes of highly correlated attributes
print(highlyCorrelated) # nos sale correlacionado con la 8(embarazos)
# return the name of the column (instead the index)
highlyCorrelated <- findCorrelation(correlationMatrix, cutoff=0.5,names=T)
print(highlyCorrelated)
# ensure results are repeatable
set.seed(7)
# prepare training scheme
control <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=10, repeats=3)
# train the model
model <- train(diabetes~., data=PimaIndiansDiabetes, method="rf", preProcess="scale", trControl=control)
# estimate variable importance
importance <- varImp(model, scale=FALSE)
# summarize importance
print(importance)
# plot importance
plot(importance)
set.seed(7)
